// Terminal-emulator philosophy: Doug McIlroy's "Write programs that do
// one thing and do it well" would have the terminal emulate a terminal
// and delegate tabs, panes, and session persistence to an external
// multiplexer such as zellij - which Ditana installs by default. The
// pragmatic problem is inline graphics inside zellij. A growing share
// of TUIs depends on inline images (yazi / lf previews, gnuplot /
// matplotlib output, document and image viewers), and under zellij the
// situation is asymmetric rather than a flat "no graphics":
//   * zellij supports Sixel (since v0.31.0, 2022) but has never
//     implemented Kitty-graphics-protocol passthrough. Only the older
//     Sixel protocol reaches the terminal through zellij, and even that
//     path is known upstream to be buggy and laggy.
//   * kitty and ghostty deliberately render NO Sixel (Kitty protocol
//     only). Inside zellij their inline images therefore break: the one
//     protocol zellij relays (Sixel) is exactly the one they refuse.
//   * foot renders Sixel, so foot + zellij DOES show inline images,
//     provided the application correctly negotiates Sixel - either by
//     detecting zellij and forcing Sixel on itself (yazi via
//     $ZELLIJ_SESSION_NAME) or by querying the terminal's graphics
//     protocol at runtime (ekphos >= v0.25.10). Applications that
//     assume the Kitty protocol or mis-detect capabilities still break.
// Net effect: the Sixel-only terminal is the more capable choice
// specifically WHEN wrapped in zellij, because Sixel is the only
// protocol that survives the multiplexer. Outside zellij the situation
// reverses - kitty/ghostty render images directly via the superior
// Kitty protocol. Ditana therefore keeps a full-featured terminal with
// its OWN tabs, splits, and image protocol as the default: it delivers
// inline graphics reliably by NOT routing through zellij at all (use
// the terminal's own splits instead). The McIlroy ideal remains a
// tie-breaker among otherwise-equivalent options, not a hard rule.
//
// Among image-capable, fully featured terminals (kitty, wezterm,
// ghostty), kitty is Ditana's default. Reasons:
//   * Stability: anecdotal reports plus tracker activity suggest
//     wezterm exhibits occasional unexplained freezes (both the
//     2024 release and the current development version); ghostty
//     still has small rough edges of its own.
//   * Hardware reach: kitty needs only OpenGL 3.3, so it also runs
//     under llvmpipe in VMs without GPU passthrough - whereas
//     ghostty requires OpenGL 4.3+ (compute shaders, SSBOs).
//   * Maturity: kitty has been a reference for image-capable
//     terminals since 2017 and ships an extensible kittens ecosystem.
// wezterm and ghostty stay as alternatives; both are excellent in
// their own right and superior to kitty in some details (e.g.
// wezterm's Lua configurability), so the choice is left to the user.
//
// Each entry below is one option in the «Terminal Emulator» radiolist
// shown under «Advanced Settings». Exactly one of install-kitty,
// install-wezterm, install-foot, install-alacritty, install-ghostty,
// install-cosmic-term, install-no-terminal is active at any time
// (radiolist semantics).

- name="install-wezterm" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="WezTerm - GPU-accelerated, X11 + Wayland, full-featured multiplexer" \
  long-description="""
WezTerm is a GPU-accelerated terminal emulator and multiplexer for X11 and Wayland.
 • Built-in tabs, splits, pane navigation, scrollback search, OSC 133 prompt markers, hyperlinks, both Sixel and the Kitty image protocol, and Lua configuration.
 • Ditana ships a zellij-style preconfiguration: Alt+1..9 switch tabs, Alt+hjkl navigate panes, Alt+Shift+hjkl create splits, Alt+m swaps panes, Alt+e dumps the scrollback into your $EDITOR. Edit or delete ~/.config/wezterm/wezterm.lua to change the bindings.
 • Packaging: named wezterm-git in the Ditana repo because upstream releases very infrequently; built natively, not pulled from the AUR.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="MIT" \
  available="`install-desktop-environment`" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages "wezterm-git" \
                  "xdg-terminal-exec-git"
    files "/etc/skel/.config/wezterm/wezterm.lua" \
          "/usr/share/pixmaps/ditana-logo-tiny.png"
    chroot-script "mkdir -p /etc/xdg" \
                  "echo org.wezfurlong.wezterm.desktop >/etc/xdg/xdg-terminals.list" \
                  "mkdir -p /etc/environment.d" \
                  "echo TERMINAL=wezterm >> /etc/environment.d/set-terminal.conf"
    mime-defaults {
        - "org.wezfurlong.wezterm.desktop" "x-scheme-handler/terminal"
    }
  }

- name="install-foot" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="foot - Wayland-native, fast, OSC-133/OSC-9 support" \
  long-description="""
foot is a Wayland-native terminal with a very small memory footprint; pick it on Wayland systems where minimalism matters more than built-in multiplexing.
 • OSC 133 semantic prompt markers - jump between prompts in scrollback and select full command output. Ditana ships shell hooks in /etc/skel/.shellrc that emit these markers in bash and zsh, scoped to foot via $TERM / $TERMINAL.
 • OSC 9 / OSC 777 desktop notifications - any shell script or CLI tool can raise "build finished" style alerts with a single printf.
 • Sixel graphics - inline image previews in TUIs such as yazi, lf, gnuplot and matplotlib.
 • Server / daemon mode (foot --server) - near-instant window spawn, noticeable under tiling compositors.
 • Multiplexer advantage: because foot renders Sixel and zellij relays Sixel, foot + zellij is currently the most reliable way to keep inline images working inside the multiplexer (yazi, and ekphos >= v0.25.10) - the one combination where graphics look the same with or without zellij.
Because foot is Wayland-only, picking it on a system that also installs XFCE auto-pulls kitty as the X11 fallback.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="MIT" \
  available="`install-wayland`" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages "foot" \
                  "libnotify" \
                  "xdg-terminal-exec-git"
    files "/etc/skel/.config/foot/foot.ini" \
          "/etc/systemd/user/foot-server.service.d/ditana-shutdown.conf"
    chroot-script "systemctl --global enable foot-server.socket" \
                  "mkdir -p /etc/xdg" \
                  "echo footclient.desktop >/etc/xdg/xdg-terminals.list"
    mime-defaults {
        - "footclient.desktop" "x-scheme-handler/terminal"
    }
  }

- name="install-alacritty" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="Alacritty - GPU-accelerated, X11 + Wayland, minimalist" \
  long-description="""
Alacritty is a GPU-accelerated terminal for X11 and Wayland that, by design, declines tabs, panes, graphics protocols, ligatures and most OSC extensions, delegating to external tools such as zellij.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="Apache-2.0" \
  available="`install-desktop-environment`" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages "alacritty" \
                  "xdg-terminal-exec-git"
    chroot-script "mkdir -p /etc/xdg" \
                  "echo Alacritty.desktop >/etc/xdg/xdg-terminals.list"
    mime-defaults {
        - "Alacritty.desktop" "x-scheme-handler/terminal"
    }
  }

- name="install-kitty" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="kitty - GPU-accelerated (OpenGL 3.3), X11 + Wayland, full-featured" \
  long-description="""
kitty is a GPU-accelerated terminal for X11 and Wayland.
 • Built-in tabs, splits, the Kitty graphics protocol, a Python kittens ecosystem and configurable shaders.
 • Needs only OpenGL 3.3, so it also runs under llvmpipe in VMs without GPU passthrough, where Ghostty fails.
 • Multiplexer note: kitty renders the Kitty protocol but no Sixel. Since zellij relays only Sixel, inline images (yazi, ekphos, image previews) break inside zellij. Use kitty's own tabs and splits for inline graphics instead of wrapping it in zellij.
Pick this for a feature-rich, batteries-included terminal across both display servers.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="GPL-3.0-only" \
  available="`install-desktop-environment`" \
  default-value="`install-desktop-environment AND NOT (install-wayland AND profile-windows)`" {
    arch-packages "kitty" \
                  "imagemagick" \
                  "python-pygments" \
                  "libcanberra" \
                  "xdg-terminal-exec-git"
    files "/etc/xdg/kitty/kitty.conf" \
          "/usr/share/pixmaps/ditana-logo-tiny.png"
    chroot-script "mkdir -p /etc/xdg" \
                  "echo kitty.desktop >/etc/xdg/xdg-terminals.list" \
                  "mkdir -p /etc/environment.d" \
                  "echo TERMINAL=kitty >> /etc/environment.d/set-terminal.conf"
    mime-defaults {
        - "kitty.desktop" "x-scheme-handler/terminal"
    }
  }

- name="install-ghostty" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="Ghostty - GPU-accelerated, modern, requires OpenGL 4.3+" \
  long-description="""
Ghostty is a modern, GPU-accelerated terminal that requires OpenGL 4.3+ (compute shaders, SSBOs).
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="MIT" \
  \ // In VMs without GPU passthrough, llvmpipe crashes on an LLVM JIT bug (MGATHER instruction selection) and softpipe only reaches OpenGL 3.3; the has-wayland-compatible-gpu check hides this option there.
  available="`install-desktop-environment AND has-wayland-compatible-gpu`" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages "ghostty" \
                  "xdg-terminal-exec-git"
    files "/etc/skel/.config/ghostty/config" \
          "/usr/share/pixmaps/ditana-logo-tiny.png"
    chroot-script "mkdir -p /etc/xdg" \
                  "echo com.mitchellh.ghostty.desktop >/etc/xdg/xdg-terminals.list" \
                  "mkdir -p /etc/environment.d" \
                  "echo TERMINAL=ghostty >> /etc/environment.d/set-terminal.conf"
    mime-defaults {
        - "com.mitchellh.ghostty.desktop" "x-scheme-handler/terminal"
    }
  }

- name="install-cosmic-term" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="COSMIC Terminal - Modern Wayland-native, GPU-accelerated" \
  long-description="""
COSMIC Terminal is a Wayland-native, GPU-accelerated terminal from System76, written in Rust on the iced toolkit, and the default on profile-windows.
 • Offered chiefly for COSMIC-desktop users and for people coming from Windows / KDE Plasma / Cinnamon / Xfce / MATE: it is the only option here with conventional GUI affordances (classic menu bar, right-click context menu, graphical preferences) rather than a keyboard-driven workflow.
 • Wayland-only; if XFCE is also installed, kitty is auto-pulled as the X11 fallback (same mechanism as for foot).
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="GPL-3.0-only" \
  available="`install-wayland`" \
  default-value="`install-wayland AND profile-windows`" {
    arch-packages "cosmic-terminal"
    chroot-script "mkdir -p /etc/xdg" \
                  "echo com.system76.CosmicTerm.desktop >/etc/xdg/xdg-terminals.list" \
                  "mkdir -p /etc/environment.d" \
                  "echo TERMINAL=cosmic-term >> /etc/environment.d/set-terminal.conf"
    mime-defaults {
        - "com.system76.CosmicTerm.desktop" "x-scheme-handler/terminal"
    }
  }

- name="install-no-terminal" \
  dialog-name="Terminal Emulator" \
  short-description="None - Do not install a terminal emulator (server / headless)" \
  long-description="""
Skip terminal emulator installation. Auto-selected for headless / server installs without a desktop environment.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value="`NOT install-desktop-environment`" {
    arch-packages ""
  }
